  <slide>
    <title>Bypass Blocks: Accessibility Requirements</title>
    <contents>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/bypass-blocks">2.4.1: Bypass Blocks</a> requires a means for keyboard only used to navigate to the main content of the page, essentially bypassing navigational and other links that appear before the main content.</li>
        <li>Typically bypass blocks is achieved with a "Skip To Main" link that is initially invisible, but appears when it receives keyboard focus.</li>
      </ul>
    </contents>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Bypass Blocks: SkipTo Script</title>
    <contents>
      <ul>
        <li>The <a href="https://github.com/a11y-tools/skipto/blob/master/README.md">SkipTo</a> script is the modern way to conform to the "<a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG/#bypass-blocks" rel="nofollow">Bypass Blocks</a>" requirement of the <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG/" rel="nofollow">Web Content Accessibility Guidelines</a>.</li>
        <li><em>All users</em> can get an outline of the major content areas on the page.</li>
        <li><em>Screen reader</em> users can get a higher level navigation menu without having to use the screen reader landmark and header navigation commands which typically include longer lists of lower level headings and less used landmarks.</li>
        <li><em>Keyboard only</em> users can more efficiently navigate to content on a page.</li>
        <li><em>Speech recognition</em> users can use the menu to more efficiently navigate to content on a page.</li>
        <li><em>Authors</em> can configure SkipTo to identify the most important regions, ideally about 7-12 items to make it easier for people to read the list and choose an option.  Remember the more items, the longer it will take for the user to identify which item they want to choose.</li>
      </ul>
    </contents>
  </slide>

